<p>A Thousand Clowns is a 1965 American <ref target="/wiki/Comedy-drama" title="Comedy-drama">comedy-drama film</ref> directed by <ref target="/wiki/Fred_Coe" title="Fred Coe">Fred Coe</ref> and starring <ref target="/wiki/Jason_Robards" title="Jason Robards">Jason Robards</ref>, <ref target="/wiki/Barbara_Harris_(actress)" title="Barbara Harris (actress)">Barbara Harris</ref>, <ref target="/wiki/Martin_Balsam" title="Martin Balsam">Martin Balsam</ref>, and <ref target="/wiki/Barry_Gordon" title="Barry Gordon">Barry Gordon</ref>. An adaptation of a 1962 play by <ref target="/wiki/Herb_Gardner" title="Herb Gardner">Herb Gardner</ref>, it tells the story of an eccentric comedy writer who is forced to conform to society to retain legal custody of his nephew.</p>
<ref target="/wiki/Jason_Robards" title="Jason Robards">Jason Robards</ref> starred in both the original <ref target="/wiki/Broadway_theatre" title="Broadway theatre">Broadway</ref> version and in the film. <ref target="/wiki/Martin_Balsam" title="Martin Balsam">Martin Balsam</ref> won an <ref target="/wiki/Academy_Awards" title="Academy Awards">Oscar</ref> for his supporting performance in the movie.

